---
import PageLayout from '@/layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import Icon from '@/components/ui/primitives/Icon/Icon.astro';
import Badge from '@/components/ui/data-display/Badge/Badge.astro';
import Card from '@/components/ui/data-display/Card/Card.astro';
import Button from '@/components/ui/form/Button/Button.astro';
import { Hero } from '@/components/hero';
import LetterGlitchBand from '@/components/patterns/LetterGlitchBand.astro';
import Accordion from '@/components/ui/overlay/Accordion/Accordion.astro';
---
<PageLayout
  title="About 701am - Earned Media & Authority Engineering"
  description="David Krug. Earned media built by someone who spent a career learning exactly how trust gets built and how machines decide who deserves it."
>
  <Hero layout="centered" size="sm" class="isolate" showHeroHalo>
    <Badge slot="badge" variant="brand" pill>
      <Icon name="user" size="sm" />
      About
    </Badge>
    <h1 slot="title" class="font-display font-semibold leading-[1.08] tracking-tight max-w-4xl mx-auto">
      <span class="text-brand-500 [-webkit-text-fill-color:var(--color-brand-500)]">Long before brands worried about</span><br />
      <span class="text-foreground [-webkit-text-fill-color:currentColor]">showing up in AI</span>
    </h1>

    <p slot="description" class="max-w-2xl mx-auto text-lg leading-relaxed" style="line-height: 1.618">
      I spent a career learning exactly how machines decide who to trust. 701am is earned media built by someone who came up through the hardest trust environment on the internet: helping people make one of the biggest decisions of their lives.
    </p>
  </Hero>

  <!-- The Origin -->
  <section class="py-28 md:py-40 bg-background-secondary">
    <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-grid opacity-[0.03] pointer-events-none" />
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 flex flex-col gap-8" data-reveal>
      <Badge variant="brand" pill class="self-start">The origin</Badge>
      <h2 class="font-display text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-semibold leading-[1.08] tracking-tight text-foreground max-w-3xl">
        I started where trust is everything: higher education.
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-foreground-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5 max-w-4xl" style="line-height: 1.618">
        <p>
          I built my career in education. Running and scaling some of the most-visited college and graduate-school decision platforms on the web.
        </p>
        <p>
          Education taught me something most marketers never have to learn the hard way: <strong class="text-foreground font-medium">you cannot buy a prospective student's trust</strong>. They research for months. They compare obsessively. They read reviews, rankings, and third-party sources, and they ignore anything that smells like an ad. The only way to win them is to <em>earn</em> a place in the sources they already trust.
        </p>
        <p>
          That is not a marketing tactic I picked up. It is the environment I grew up in professionally. Where credibility was not a nice-to-have. It was the entire business.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Craft -->
  <section class="py-28 md:py-40 bg-background">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 flex flex-col gap-8" data-reveal>
      <Badge variant="brand" pill class="self-start">The craft</Badge>
      <h2 class="font-display text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-semibold leading-[1.08] tracking-tight text-foreground max-w-3xl">
        As Director of SEO, I learned how authority actually gets built.
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-foreground-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5 max-w-4xl" style="line-height: 1.618">
        <p>
          Search engines do not rank you because you ask nicely. They rank you because the rest of the internet vouches for you. Through credible mentions, authoritative links, and signals of genuine trust accumulated over time.
        </p>
        <p>
          I spent years as Director of SEO learning to engineer exactly that. Not tricks. Not hacks that died with the next algorithm update. The durable work: building real authority, earning coverage from sources that mattered, and understanding at a structural level how a machine decides which voices deserve to be amplified and which get buried.
        </p>
        <p>
          I got very good at making sure the right people found the right thing at the moment they were deciding.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Throughline -->
  <section class="py-28 md:py-40 bg-background-secondary">
    <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-b from-brand-500/[0.02] to-transparent pointer-events-none" />
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 flex flex-col gap-8" data-reveal>
      <Badge variant="brand" pill class="self-start">The throughline</Badge>
      <h2 class="font-display text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-semibold leading-[1.08] tracking-tight text-foreground max-w-3xl">
        Then the machines changed. The skill did not.
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-foreground-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5 max-w-4xl" style="line-height: 1.618">
        <p>
          Here is what almost no one in marketing has fully connected: <strong class="text-foreground font-medium">AI search runs on the same logic I have worked in my entire career</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          When ChatGPT or Google's AI names "the best" option in a category, it is not pulling from whoever spent the most on ads. It is pulling from the brands with credible, third-party authority behind them. The same signals that decided who ranked. The same trust that decided which schools students chose.
        </p>
        <p>
          I have been building those signals for over a decade. The vocabulary changed from "rankings" to "AI answers." The discipline is identical. While most agencies are just now discovering this shift, I have spent my whole career living inside it.
        </p>
        <p>
          That is the unfair advantage I bring to earned media. I do not see it as press for press's sake. I see it as <strong class="text-foreground font-medium">authority engineering</strong>. The work of making sure that when it matters most, the systems people rely on point to you.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What 701am Stands For -->
  <section class="py-28 md:py-40 bg-background">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 flex flex-col gap-8" data-reveal>
      <Badge variant="brand" pill class="self-start">What 701am stands for</Badge>
      <h2 class="font-display text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-semibold leading-[1.08] tracking-tight text-foreground max-w-3xl">
        Earned, not bought. Built, not borrowed.
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-foreground-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5 max-w-4xl" style="line-height: 1.618">
        <p>
          701am exists on one belief: the most valuable thing a brand can own is the trust of the sources its buyers, and now its machines, rely on. You can rent attention with ad spend. You can only <em>earn</em> authority. And once you have earned it, it compounds in ways no budget can replicate.
        </p>
        <p>
          Every engagement is run with that in mind. No vanity metrics. No spray-and-pray pitching. Just credible coverage, in the right places, that builds something durable.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- How I Work -->
  <section class="py-28 md:py-40 bg-background-secondary">
    <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-grid opacity-[0.03] pointer-events-none" />
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 flex flex-col gap-8" data-reveal>
      <Badge variant="brand" pill class="self-start">How I work</Badge>
      <h2 class="font-display text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-semibold leading-[1.08] tracking-tight text-foreground max-w-3xl">
        You get the operator, not an account exec.
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-foreground-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5 max-w-4xl" style="line-height: 1.618">
        <p>
          I am not a layer of management between you and a junior team. When you work with 701am, you work with me. The strategy, the pitching, and the SEO-and-authority thinking that most earned-media shops simply do not have in their DNA.
        </p>
        <p>
          Fixed scope. Transparent reporting. Senior judgment on every decision.
        </p>
        <p>
          A decade of figuring out how trust gets built and how machines decide who deserves it. Pointed directly at your brand.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section class="py-28 md:py-40 bg-background">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 flex flex-col gap-10">
      <div class="flex flex-col items-center gap-6 text-center" data-reveal>
        <Badge variant="brand" pill>Good to know</Badge>
        <h2 class="font-display text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-semibold leading-[1.08] tracking-tight text-foreground">
          Frequently asked questions
        </h2>
      </div>
      <div data-reveal>
        <Card variant="elevated" padding="lg">
          <Accordion
            items={[
              {
                title: 'How is this different from a PR agency?',
                content: 'You work directly with me, not a rotating junior team. Fixed scope, transparent reporting, and a focus on the outcomes that matter now. Including AI-search visibility, which most agencies have not caught up to.'
              },
              {
                title: 'Can you guarantee coverage?',
                content: 'No honest operator guarantees specific placements. Journalists decide. What I guarantee is the targeted work, the right angles, and full transparency on every pitch and result.'
              },
              {
                title: 'What does it cost?',
                content: 'Sprints are fixed-price and scoped to your goals. Book a fit call and I will quote you directly. No drawn-out proposal process.'
              },
              {
                title: 'How fast can we start?',
                content: 'This week, if there is a fit. I take on a limited number of sprints at a time.'
              },
            ]}
          />
        </Card>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="relative z-10 py-28 md:py-40 bg-background-secondary overflow-hidden">
    <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-b from-brand-500/[0.03] via-transparent to-brand-500/[0.03] pointer-events-none" />
    <div class="glitch:hidden mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 text-center" data-reveal>
      <h2 class="font-display text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-semibold leading-[1.08] tracking-tight text-foreground mb-6 text-balance">
        The brands that win the next decade will be the ones the machines trust.
      </h2>
      <p class="text-lg text-foreground-muted mb-10 text-balance leading-relaxed" style="line-height: 1.618">
        Let's make sure that is you.
      </p>
      <Button size="lg" href="/contact" class="cta-btn-brand">
        Book a 15-minute fit call
        <Icon name="arrow-right" size="sm" />
      </Button>
    </div>

    <LetterGlitchBand>
      <h2 class="font-display text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-semibold leading-[1.08] tracking-tight text-foreground mb-6 text-balance">
        The brands that win the next decade will be the ones the machines trust.
      </h2>
      <p class="text-lg text-foreground-muted mb-10 text-balance leading-relaxed" style="line-height: 1.618">
        Let's make sure that is you.
      </p>
      <Button size="lg" href="/contact" class="hero-btn-brand">
        Book a 15-minute fit call
        <Icon name="arrow-right" size="sm" />
      </Button>
    </LetterGlitchBand>
  </section>
</PageLayout>
